                            <p>Most notably in our statistical analysis, the funds large donors raise for Black women running in competitive primaries are not comparable to their donations to other demographic groups, especially white women. Large donors
                                on average raised a third of the funds for Black women's campaigns ($161,000 on average) compared to what they raised for white women ($527,000). And, with the exception of open seat primary contests, men of color raise
                                more than white men.</p>

                            <p>The fundraising advantages that help women fill historic fundraising gaps on average help white women, not the diverse range of candidates who are running for office. In open seat primary contests, which is where the most progress
                                toward electing a more diverse Congress can be made, white women raise twice as much as women of color on average in general election contests.</p>

                            <p>The intersectional effects on large individual donations hold even when district-level characteristics and factors are taken into account. For instance, Black candidates often run in districts with lower household median income
                                levels than white candidates, and Black women in Congress serve, on average, in less competitive districts where fundraising and spending might be lower. Another example of a district-level characteristic is the percentage
                                of white people living in a district, which affects campaigns' level of fundraising.</p>

                            <p>Traditionally, candidates rely most heavily on donations from "large" individual donors — those who give over $200 to the specific candidate in the cycle — to fund their campaigns. Candidates typically make up the rest of their
                                fundraising with money from political action committees and "small" individual donors — those who give less than $201 to the candidate in the cycle. Some candidates also supplement that fundraising with significant self-financing,
                                although this is fairly uncommon.</p>

                            <p>The biggest question remains: Why do large donors donate so much less on average for Black women candidates than candidates in other demographic groups, even when all other factors are held relatively constant? Given that large
                                individual donors are the primary source of campaign money, this wide gap could cause major problems for women trying to run competitive and successful campaigns, and may be a sign of who has access to fundraising networks
                                from the beginning.</p>

                            <p>To answer this, we only looked at Democratic candidates given how few Black women candidates run in competitive primaries for the Republican party.</p>

                            <p>White women do receive more money on average from "early major donors" than Black women, however, the biggest issue is that large donors who are retirees and people who work in education — the two sources of funds that are
                                traditionally the largest for Democrats — give significantly less to Black women than their other Democratic counterparts.

                            </p>
                            <p>Although retirees and people working in education are of interest because of how significant they are as donors to Democrats, there were few interest groups or industries where Black women outraised white women on average,
                                and only two of those interest groups give significant money — women's issues and human rights. Other organized identity interest groups such as Emily's List <a target="_blank" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/04/us/politics/emilys-list-midterm-elections.html">have been accused of prioritizing white women</a>                                in the past, however our data shows that this was not the case in 2020. Given that Black women were outraised by white women generally, it seems that these major donors in some of the Democratic party's mainstay industries
                                are driving these major gaps in campaign support.</p>

                            <p>The systematic racism that surrounds American life bleeds into our elections system in many ways, especially through the biased perceptions of "viability," notable hesitation from the party establishment, and, by far the biggest
                                barrier to entry: fundraising. Raising enough money to run a viable campaign attracts big donors and is crucial for candidates in their primary elections, according to <a target="_blank" href="https://www.politico.com/news/2020/07/20/congressional-candidates-of-color-366416">Politico's interviews</a>                                with two dozen candidates of color, lawmakers and strategists.</p>

                            <p>Politicians and observers often point to fundraising as one of the biggest barriers to running in the first place, which ends up helping well-established and well-represented demographic groups of white and male candidates
                                who make up the majority of those running for office. Funding disparities affect candidates' vote shares, reinforcing electoral disadvantages for Black women, Latina women, Indigenous women, MENA women, and Asian and Pacific
                                Islander women.</p>

                            <p>Moreover, electoral barriers do not disappear with equitable campaign receipts. <a target="_blank" href="https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1300/J014v25n04_01">Research</a> points to the fact that women, especially women
                                of color, may require more financial investment to receive equitable outcomes compared to men running for office. These intersectional racial barriers support a system that allows Congress to remain a predominantly white,
                                male and privileged institution.</p>

                            <p>This mirrors our <a target="_blank" href="https://www.pgpf.org/us-2050/research-projects/Race-Gender-and-Money-in-Politics-Campaign-Finance-and-Federal-Candidates-in-the-2018-Midterms">previous work</a> showing that Black women
                                raise significantly less from large donors in all types of races. In 2018, we found that women, especially Black women, Latina women, Indigenous women, MENA women, and Asian and Pacific Islander women faced unique fundraising
                                barriers while running in congressional races. Those barriers persisted in 2020.</p>

                            <p>Moreover, our research points to a reliance on small donations for women candidates. Large donors as a whole consistently underfund many demographic groups of women. In other words, women have to raise higher numbers of small
                                donations to reach aggregate totals comparable to white and/or male counterparts, who often raise the most money from large donors.</p>

                            <p>Although large donors are not the only source of fundraising, they are the most significant source for most candidates. The differences in fundraising between Black and white women in donations from small donors are less extreme.</p>

                            <p>Small donors seem to be the place where racial differences in fundraising begin to equalize, and as a whole, small donors are more representative of the gender, class, and race demographics of diverse voting constituencies.
                                However, small dollar fundraising is difficult to bring to scale. Sometimes candidates can build a successful campaign by relying on small donors, especially if the contest catches a high-profile and becomes a target for
                                major online fundraising, but this is not the norm.</p>

