                            <p>Candidates from underrepresented demographic groups typically must learn how to raise the necessary funds to run a successful campaign without relying on traditional sources of cash — such as establishment networks of large
                                donors or money from national party sources including the DCCC or DSCC. Identity interest groups historically have stepped in to fill these historic gender and racial gaps, as Politico describes, "[t]he financial lifelines
                                for many candidates of color, particularly early on in the races, have often come from groups like Emily's List, Higher Heights and the Collective PAC — groups that backed many of the Democratic candidates of color who
                                won in 2018."</p>

                            <p>Another trend responding to this fundraising gap is the rise in the number of women donor networks and PACs and their concentration of support for Democratic women candidates. This has created more equitable financial conditions
                                between women and men in recent elections. As we found in 2018, much of this increase in female fundraising was driven by female candidates raising a disproportionate amount of money from female donors. Women relied more
                                heavily on women donors than in prior cycles starting in 2018, and the increase in Democratic women donors in 2018 helped elect many Democratic women to Congress.</p>

                            <p><a target="_blanK" href="https://www.opensecrets.org/news/2020/12/women-ran-won-donate-record-numbers-2020-nimp/">For the past few cycles</a>, OpenSecrets has documented how political participation by women, both as candidates
                                and as donors, has risen in the wake of the 2016 election. That trend spiked during the 2018 midterm elections and continued into the all-time most expensive 2020 election, which included many high-profile congressional,
                                senatorial and presidential primaries that ushered in historic moments for women of both parties.</p>

                            <p>More women than ever before won congressional elections in 2020, and now occupy 27 percent of the chamber's seats, mostly due to the successes of the Democratic party. Looking at the campaigns of four women — two Democrats
                                and two Republicans — who unseated incumbent members of Congress in 2020 illustrates the unique influences that interacted with the 2020 elections.</p>

                            <p>Of these women, two — Reps. <a href="/members-of-congress/cori-bush/summary?cid=N00039373">Cori Bush</a> (D-Mo.) and <a href="/members-of-congress/marie-newman/summary?cid=N00040891">Marie Newman</a> (D-Ill.) — represent solid-blue
                                districts in the Midwest. Two — Reps. <a href="/members-of-congress/michelle-steel/summary?cid=N00044501">Michelle Steel</a> (R-Calif.) and <a href="/members-of-congress/maria-salazar/summary?cid=N00042810">Maria Elvira Salazar</a>                                (R-Fla.) — represent coastal districts in the nation's Sun Belt. Bush is Black and Newman is white. Steel is the first Korean-American woman in Congress, and Salazar is the daughter of Cuban immigrants.</p>

                            <p>Bush and Newman mounted successful primary campaigns against Democrats to their right, running on their support for social justice and economic equality. Steel and Salazar took down Democratic incumbents with "small ‘c' conservative"
                                ideals in their respective seaside swing districts where voters narrowly favored President Joe Biden over Donald Trump. All four races drew national attention and millions in out-of-district donations.</p>

                            <p>The campaigns and victories of Newman, Bush, Steel and Salazar tell many stories. From one perspective, they tell a tale of growing partisanship.</p>

                            <p>Four moderate incumbent Democrats lost their seats — two to Republicans, two to progressives.</p>

                            <p>They tell another story about first- and second-generation immigrants finding footholds in the GOP, and yet another about the power of social justice activism and advocacy to galvanize Democratic voters and donors. Each of
                                the four first-year members plays a part in a larger narrative too, about progress toward gender parity and demographic representation in America's halls of power. All four lawmakers demonstrate how women from a range of
                                backgrounds who hold a diversity of political convictions can run, fundraise and win.</p>

                            <p>The Republicans, Salazar and Steel, raised and spent more than <a href="/elections-overview/election-trends">the average House candidate</a> on their respective elections. Steel brought in a whopping $6.3 million, narrowly
                                beating out incumbent Democrat <a href="/members-of-congress/harley-rouda/summary?cid=N00040666">Harley Rouda</a> who raised just less than $6 million. Large donations from individuals made up a plurality of Steel's total
                                haul, and she self-funded a significant portion of her campaign, loaning herself nearly $1.9 million. Salazar also infused her campaign with around nearly $163,000 from her personal coffers. The Florida lawmaker raised
                                a total of $3.7 million, just short of incumbent <a href="/members-of-congress/donna-shalala/summary?cid=N00042811">Donna Shalala</a>'s $3.8 million overall haul. Like Steel, Salazar's largest donor base were individuals
                                who gave $200 or more.</p>

                            <p>Bush and Newman, who ran in safe-blue districts, raised and spent significantly less than Salazar and Steel in their 2020 general election campaigns. A significant majority (85 percent) of Bush's fundraising came from out-of-state
                                donors, perhaps thanks to outside spending by high-profile national groups like the Justice Democrats. Small-dollar donors made up 55 percent of Bush's total fundraising haul. Contributions from PACs, including Justice
                                Democrats and the Service Employees International Union, comprised slightly more than 8 percent of her fundraising total.</p>

                            <p>Newman gained more traction with PACs than Bush, picking up endorsements from deep-pocketed Democratic groups including Emily's List, PAC to the Future and J Street. PACs gave Newman almost 12 percent of her fundraising total
                                in the 2020 cycle. Large individual donors represented the largest share of Newman's supporters, and small donors gave less than 36 percent of her overall war chest. Like Bush, more than half (53 percent) of donations to
                                Newman's campaign came from out of state.</p>

                            <p>Ultimately, both Bush and Newman far outpaced their Republican general election opponents in both raising and spending. Despite the similarities in their campaigns — both Newman and Bush are progressives, mothers and Midwesterners
                                — Newman's overall 2020 fundraising outcome was approximately double Bush's.</p>

