                            <p>Democratic women donors raised more money for white women than any other demographic group. Within open seat and challenger races in competitive primaries, women gave the most to white women candidates both in total sums and
                                in the proportion of the money going to their races. In primary contests where women ran as challengers, women gave on average $490,000 to white women, compared to $118,000 on average for women of color. In open seat races,
                                on average women gave $184,000 to white women, compared to $82,000 to women of color.</p>

                            <p>Some of the largest fundraising dates in 2020, particularly for Democrats, fell around events that had significant gendered and racialized implications. ActBlue reported its <a href="https://www.opensecrets.org/news/2021/02/2020-cycle-cost-14p4-billion-doubling-16/">largest fundraising</a>                                totals in history the day after Supreme Court Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg died. Additionally, fundraising spiked in June as the nation faced the aftermath of the brutal police murder of George Floyd in Minneapolis, Min.
                                Sen. <a href="/members-of-congress/kamala-harris/summary?cid=N00036915">Kamala Harris</a>'s selection as the Democratic running mate also led to increased donations to Democratic candidates, led by women donors.</p>

                            <p><a target="_blank" href="https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.1177/1065912917698044">Research</a> points to Democratic women donors exhibiting a gender affinity effect in their support of women running for office. That creates
                                a gap in fundraising trends between Republican women and Democratic women as partisan donor pools tend to support Democratic candidates. However, that is starting to change with the rise in support for Republican women
                                from <a target="_blank" href="https://www.opensecrets.org/news/2020/12/women-ran-won-donate-record-numbers-2020-nimp/">GOP women donor networks</a>.</p>

                            <p>In the competitive primaries of the 2020 elections, on average, Black women (40 percent), Asian women (39 percent), white women (39 percent) and Hispanic women (38 percent) got the highest proportion of their funds from women
                                donors — all higher percentages than their male counterparts. However, there are major discrepancies within the average sums that each demographic group raised from women, especially concerning the average sums raised by
                                women for Black women. White women raised $245,000 from women on average, where Black women raised $71,000 from women on average.</p>

                            <p>Although 2020 elected a record number of women, racial minorities and members of the LGBTQ+ community, where the money behind their campaigns came from does not reflect the diversity of America's ZIP codes. Looking at the 100
                                ZIP codes where residents donated the most money in the 2020 elections ($1.4 billion), they are majority white areas with an average household income of $540,000. The average household income in the U.S. in 2020 is estimated
                                to be $87,000. The ZIP codes where residents donated the most money to the elections are on average, by far, less diverse and far wealthier than most of the ZIP codes in the country. And the majority of that money comes
                                from male donors.</p>

                            <p>Despite these systematic barriers that make fundraising a gatekeeping mechanism for many demographic groups of candidates, leaders from within these communities organize to fill these gaps. From Politico, "[t]he successes so
                                far in 2020, however, are not the result of a recent cultural movement. Black and Latino political leaders have spent years building up their own powerful networks devoted to hoisting their candidates against the self-funders
                                and well-connected, especially in previous cycles when party organs sometimes overlooked candidates of color, stifling their ability to fundraise."</p>

                            <p><i><a href="https://www.opensecrets.org/about/staff.php#mcfadden">Alyce McFadden</a> contributed to this report.</i></p>

